         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1958a"/><citedRange>155</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">all enemies he defeats, therefore virtue is the best. (2. And furthermore): Of virtue/merit this is the one quality superior to all for us: that it is</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a1 #a2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:hackstein1995"/><citedRange>90</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1954"/><citedRange>724</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>257f, 259</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Dies ist die alles überragende gute Eigenschaft der verdienstvollen Taten für uns, dass sie da nicht durch Feuer verbrannt werden, nicht durch Wasser fortgespült werden, nicht von Königen weggenommen [und] auch nicht von Dieben gestohlen werden können.</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">This is the good property, exceeding all [else], of the deeds of merit for us, that they cannot be burned by fire, be swept away by water, be taken away by kings [and] be stolen by thieves either.</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>257-8, 259</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a1 #a2 #a3 #a4 #a5 #a6 #b1 #b2 #b3 #b4 #b5 #b6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:sieg1944"/><citedRange>17</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">not burned with fire, not flooded away by water, [that it] cannot be taken away by kings [and that] further they cannot be stolen by thieves.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2 #a3 #a4 #a5 #a6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">And when a being lies on its deathbed, surrounded by all illnesses, and is going to (another) world without consciousness and without the beloved, at that moment [its] energy is not of any use, nor are [its] art, [its] wisdom, [its] beauty, [its] father, [its] mother, [its] sister, [its] brother, [its] wife, [its] sons, [its] house, or [its] possession[s] of any use—only [its] merit is of use at that moment.  (cf 17)</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>249</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>172</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1952"/><citedRange>36</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">And when a being lies on its deathbed, surrounded by all illnesses, and is going to (another) world without consciousness and without love,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>86</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">at that moment [its] energy is not of any use, nor are [its] art,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4 #a5 #a6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1983"/><citedRange>35</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[its] wisdom, [its] beauty, [its] father, [its] mother, [its] sister, [its] brother, [its] wife, [its] sons, [its] house, or [its] possession[s]</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">of any use – only [its] virtue/merit is of use at that moment. || In the H.-tune: || Virtue/merit is its protection</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">virtue/merit ..., virtue is its companion, virtue is comforting him. Merit drives away its fears, the ? of a bad incarnation, merit</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>245</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1972"/><citedRange>450</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">follows it in all incarnations, gives him divine and human pleasures. With merit therefore like</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1952"/><citedRange>30</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... cannot be achieved by the beings. 1. || And since virtues are the source and the root of all good qualities,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3 #b4 #b5 #b6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1997"/><citedRange>138</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(the requirement?) for all perfections, [and since they] are loved by all good beings,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1958a"/><citedRange>153</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[since they] spread the good reputation, [since] they make possible a joyful dignity and they also cause an end to all sufferings, therefore in my opinion merit is the very best</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">and superior to all. These five princes having told their own advantages in this way, thereupon again</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6 txt:m-a15#a1"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1986"/><citedRange>125</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Nachdem die fünf Prinzen auf solche Weise je ihre Vorzüge gesagt hatten, sprechen sie dann wieder zueinander: ...</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">After the five princes each had {sic!} spoken their merits, they again speak/say to each other: ...</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>321</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
